export const updateMeta = {
  date: '2026-05-25',
  title: 'Buyer health-tests page refresh: structured BreederHQ profile bullets + marketplace-signal paragraph + two buyer-facing FAQs',
  tags: ['buyers', 'health-tests', 'seo', 'content'],
};
---
<article class="border-l-4 border-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] pl-6">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">May 25, 2026</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4">Refreshed <a href="/buyers/health-tests" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">/buyers/health-tests</a> from an AirOps content review. Unlike the prior two workflow-page refreshes, this AirOps suggestion proposed a substantial pivot of the page into breeder-facing software-selection content (digital recordkeeping H2, tool comparison table, RFID guidance, common mistakes section). Skipped that entirely because this is a buyer education page, not a breeder how-to. Applied only the buyer-facing improvements.</p>

  <div class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
    <p><strong>What was added:</strong></p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
      <li>Expanded the "How breeders manage health testing" section with a structured 5-item bullet list of what's tracked at the animal profile level inside BreederHQ: genetic results, physical evaluations, vaccinations and medication history, COI and pedigrees, uploaded lab reports and certificates. Buyer-facing diligence reference.</li>
      <li>New marketplace-signal paragraph: when a buyer looks at a BreederHQ listing, they can see the documentation that supports it, drawn from the breeder's actual program records, not a self-reported claim. Aligned with the locked trust posture (no verification claims, just connected data).</li>
      <li>Tightened the closing line: "Organized health records are a sign of a serious breeding program that prioritizes animal welfare" → "Organized health records are one of the clearest signals of a serious breeding program." Removed the generic welfare clause; sharpened the trust-signal framing.</li>
      <li>Two new FAQ entries (added to both the rendered section and the schema.org FAQPage JSON-LD): "What should a digital health record include for a breeding animal?" and "How do breeders share health records with buyers?" Both are buyer-facing diligence questions.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Fixes folded in:</strong></p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
      <li>Cost FAQ: changed "$500-2000+" to "several hundred to several thousand dollars" (unsupported precision; AirOps' softer wording is more defensible). Also fixed the faux em dash ("cost more-the testing expense") to a colon ("cost more: the testing expense"). Applied to both schema array and rendered FAQ.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>What was deliberately skipped:</strong></p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
      <li><em>"Last updated: June 2025"</em> stamp — stale and not used on these pages.</li>
      <li>Entire proposed "How to track health records digitally" H2 with sub-sections (what belongs in a digital record, core workflow, choosing the right tool, physical identification, common mistakes) — breeder content on a buyer page. If we want this material, it belongs on a workflow page, not on /buyers/health-tests.</li>
      <li>Tool-comparison table recommending "mobile livestock apps", "mobile pet health apps", and "veterinary practice management systems" — recommends specific non-BreederHQ tool categories on our own buyer-education page, and the buyer isn't the audience choosing software anyway.</li>
      <li>"purpose-built tools" hedge replacing "tools like BreederHQ" — over-engineering; the direct mention works fine on a buyer-education page.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Two pre-existing faux-em-dash typos noted but not touched in this pass (would be a separate em-dash scrub): "conditions-those require individual testing" (Section 6) and several species-list entries that use " - " as a faux dash ("HYPP ... - especially Quarter Horses", "G6S ... - especially Nubians", "LWO ... - Paint Horses").</p>
  </div>
</article>
